\section{Mayer-Vietoris LES sequence (iter-022)}

After Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta} the third Mayer-Vietoris LES building block --- the connecting homomorphism $\delta$ --- is in scope. Combined with the iter-017 building blocks $\toBiprod$ (sum of two restriction maps) and $\fromBiprod$ (difference of two restriction maps), all three pieces of the LES are available. Iter-022 packages them into the standard $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}$-form sequence, mirroring Mathlib \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/MayerVietoris.lean} L120--122.

\begin{definition}[Mayer-Vietoris LES sequence (iter-022)]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_sequence}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_sequence}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category equipped with a Grothendieck topology $J$ on which $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\Type\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $\HasExt\,(\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$ all hold. Let $S : J.\MayerVietorisSquare$, $F : \Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$, and $n_0, n_1 \in \mathbb N$ with $n_0 + 1 = n_1$. The \emph{Mayer-Vietoris long exact sequence} of $F$ at the square $S$ and adjacent degrees $(n_0, n_1)$ is the $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}$-form sequence
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence}\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h \;:=\; \mathtt{ComposableArrows.mk_5}\,(\toBiprod\,n_0)\,(\fromBiprod\,n_0)\,(\delta\,n_0\,n_1\,h)\,(\toBiprod\,n_1)\,(\fromBiprod\,n_1)
  \]
  in $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}\,\AddCommGrpCat\,5$, where the abbreviated arguments are $\toBiprod\,n := \HModulePrime\_\toBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n$, $\fromBiprod\,n := \HModulePrime\_\fromBiprod\,k\,S\,F\,n$, and $\delta\,n_0\,n_1\,h := \HModulePrime\_\delta\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h$.
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \uses{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_toBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_fromBiprod, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta}
  Direct mirror of Mathlib's $\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.MayerVietorisSquare.sequence}$ (\texttt{MayerVietoris.lean} L120--122) with $F.\cohomologyPresheaf \rightarrow \HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F$ and the iter-021 $\delta$ in place of Mathlib's $S.\delta\,F$. The body is a one-line application of $\mathtt{ComposableArrows.mk_5}$ (\texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/ComposableArrows.lean}) which assembles five composable morphisms $f_0 : X_0 \to X_1$, $f_1 : X_1 \to X_2$, \ldots, $f_4 : X_4 \to X_5$ into a $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}\,C\,5$ object. Body:
  \begin{lstlisting}
  ComposableArrows.mk₅ (HModule'_toBiprod k S F n₀) (HModule'_fromBiprod k S F n₀)
    (HModule'_δ k S F n₀ n₁ h)
    (HModule'_toBiprod k S F n₁) (HModule'_fromBiprod k S F n₁)
  \end{lstlisting}
  The codomain $\mathtt{ComposableArrows}\,\AddCommGrpCat\,5$ inherits the $\AddCommGrpCat$-flavor from each individual building block (each lands in $\AddCommGrpCat$-morphisms because the iter-016 $\HModulePrime\_\cohomologyPresheaf\,k\,F\,n$ always lands in $C^{op} \to \AddCommGrpCat$, regardless of the value-category $\ModuleCat\,k$ of $F$ itself).

  Declared as $\mathtt{noncomputable\ abbrev}$ (matches Mathlib L120). The $\mathtt{abbrev}$ form is required so that downstream code in iter-023+ $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequenceIso}$ and iter-024+ $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{sequence\_exact}$ can unfold the body via $\mathtt{dsimp}$ to access $\mathtt{mk_5}$'s field-projection simp lemmas, which require unfoldability of the carrier. Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-022) confirms the body typechecks end-to-end, kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Why iter-022 scope is just the sequence, not sequence+iso+exactness]
  Mathlib's MV-LES build-out continues from $\delta$ as: sequence (L120--122) $\to$ sequence-iso to $\Ext.\mathtt{contravariantSequence}$ (L124--138) $\to$ exactness theorem (L140--141) $\to$ $\delta$-zero $\mathtt{simp}$ companions (L143--149). The sequence-iso L124--138 is the technical heart: it requires four substantial auxiliary lemmas (Mathlib L48--106) involving $\Ext.\mathtt{biprodAddEquiv}$ and the $\AddCommGrpCat$-side biproduct-vs-product $\mathtt{addEquiv}$, all of which transfer to the $\ModuleCat\,k$ flavor but require careful handling of the per-fiber $\AddCommGrpCat$-vs-$\ModuleCat\,k$ distinction. Iter-022 lays only the sequence (the smallest useful unit downstream of iter-021); iter-023 will scaffold the four auxiliary lemmas + the sequence-iso (the substantive multi-iteration work); iter-024 will scaffold the exactness theorem + the $\mathtt{simp}$ companions.

